&lt;p>The configuration of the app registration is now complete.&lt;/p>
&lt;h3 id="run-the-script-to-get-an-attendance-report">Run the Script to get an Attendance Report
&lt;/h3>&lt;p>The script can be found in my &lt;a class="link" href="https://github.com/mozziemozz/TeamsPhoneAutomation/blob/main/Scripts/MicrosoftGraph/Teams/GetTeamsAttendanceReportAsApp.ps1" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>Teams Phone Automation Repo&lt;/a> on GitHub. If you want to make use of the secret encryption feature, you&amp;rsquo;ll need to clone the entire repo because of the dependencies of other files in the repo.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>To be able to retrieve an attendance report from Microsoft Graph, we need a meeting id. Unfortunately, this is not your typical GUID you could easily find in TAC. But we can, however find it easy enough by passing a &lt;strong>Join meeting ID&lt;/strong>.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://heusser.pro/p/get-microsoft-teams-meeting-attendance-report-through-graph-api-lhpctbnzht7z/image-25.png"
width="1734"
height="957"
srcset="https://heusser.pro/p/get-microsoft-teams-meeting-attendance-report-through-graph-api-lhpctbnzht7z/image-25_hu_280817be74e3cb60.png 480w, https://heusser.pro/p/get-microsoft-teams-meeting-attendance-report-through-graph-api-lhpctbnzht7z/image-25_hu_6a7d35596415abd3.png 1024w"
loading="lazy"
decoding="async"
alt="Meeting Id example"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="181"
data-flex-basis="434px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Luckily, anyone that was invited to the meeting in question can view the Meeting ID and send it to you. Alternatively, the meeting invite could also be forwarded to you. The meeting Id is located below the join link.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://heusser.pro/p/get-microsoft-teams-meeting-attendance-report-through-graph-api-lhpctbnzht7z/image-17.png"
width="1997"
height="1139"
srcset="https://heusser.pro/p/get-microsoft-teams-meeting-attendance-report-through-graph-api-lhpctbnzht7z/image-17_hu_314ba5c68f1d6fe4.png 480w, https://heusser.pro/p/get-microsoft-teams-meeting-attendance-report-through-graph-api-lhpctbnzht7z/image-17_hu_c6833f7fcbdbf8fe.png 1024w"
loading="lazy"
decoding="async"
alt="Meeting ID in meeting invite body"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="175"
data-flex-basis="420px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Once you have this ID, you&amp;rsquo;re ready to get the attendance report through PowerShell.&lt;/p>
&lt;h4 id="teams-application-access-policy">Teams Application Access Policy
&lt;/h4>&lt;p>The Graph permissions alone are not enough to access the attendance report. We also need to create a new Teams Application Access Policy which includes the app id of the newly created Entra ID app and grant it to the meeting organizer. This is how you can do it in PowerShell.&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div class="chroma">
&lt;table class="lntable">&lt;tr>&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code>&lt;span class="lnt">1
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">2
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-powershell" data-lang="powershell">&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="c"># Create a new Teams Application Access Policy&lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="nb">New-CsApplicationAccessPolicy&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">-Identity&lt;/span> &lt;span class="nv">$applicationAccessPolicyName&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">-AppIds&lt;/span> &lt;span class="nv">$AppId&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">-Description&lt;/span> &lt;span class="s2">&amp;#34;Access Meeting Data as Entra ID app on behalf of user&amp;#34;&lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>&lt;a class="link" href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/teams/new-csapplicationaccesspolicy?view=teams-ps" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>New-CsApplicationAccessPolicy&lt;/a>&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div class="chroma">
&lt;table class="lntable">&lt;tr>&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code>&lt;span class="lnt">1
&lt;/span>&lt;span class="lnt">2
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-powershell" data-lang="powershell">&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="c"># Assign a Teams Application Access Policy to a user&lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="nb">Grant-CsApplicationAccessPolicy&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">-Identity&lt;/span> &lt;span class="nv">$UserId&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">-PolicyName&lt;/span> &lt;span class="nv">$applicationAccessPolicyName&lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>&lt;a class="link" href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/teams/grant-csapplicationaccesspolicy?view=teams-ps" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>Grant-CsApplicationAccessPolicy&lt;/a>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>But the script does all of this automatically for you.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://heusser.pro/p/get-microsoft-teams-meeting-attendance-report-through-graph-api-lhpctbnzht7z/image-19.png"
